UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0022199687800247
AB  - A continuum of abilities is incorporated into a two-factor, two-good model of human capital and international trade. Individuals can become either unskilled or skilled workers. Those individuals who become skilled workers acquire human capital in proportion to their ability. The value of the marginal product of skilled workers is differentiated from their net earnings. The Samuelson result of factor price equalization holds only for the marginal value product. However, the net earnings as well as the lifetime earnings of skilled workers do not equalize, and in fact can diverge as a result of trade.
