T1  - The impact of supply shocks on exchange rates and interest rates: Does the Marshall-Lerner condition matter?
AU  - Lawrence, Colin
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 22
IS  - 3
SP  - 321
EP  - 337
PY  - 1987
DA  - 1987/05/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0022-1996(87)80026-0
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0022199687800260
AB  - We examine the dynamic response of the exchange rate, the terms of trade and interest rates to supply shocks in a rational expectation (stochastic) environment. We establish the proposition that the Marshall-Lerner elasticity condition is sufficient to guarantee that an exogenous increase in real economic growth will appreciate the exchange rate, regardless of assumptions concerning market clearing and price flexibility. In specialized cases the traditional Marshall-Lerner condition is sufficient to establish propositions concerning exchange rate overshooting, the direction and magnitude of financial asset price movements and relative volatilities under flexible versus anticipatory pricing regimes.
