AB  - In a three-country model of international trade, the price effects of anti-dumping laws and of tariffs in the presence of anti-dumping laws may be counter-intuitive. The application of an anti-dumping law may lead to a decline in the price of an imported good in the protecting country or an increase in the price of the good in the original host country. The imposition of an import tariff in the presence of an anti-dumping law may result in a decline in domestic price of the import in the policy-active country.
