AB  - This paper studies the effects of a temporary import quota on the real exchange rate and the current-account response is determined by the interaction between two opposing forces: the intertemporal relative-price effect tends to improve the current account, while the wealth the intertemporal relative-price effect tends to improve the current account, while the wealth effect contributes to a deterioration. For a sufficiently low degree of intertemporal consumption substitution, the wealth effect is shown to dominate. In this event, the current account deteriorates in response to a temporary quota and improves only after the quota is lifted.
